Data Mining for Business Intelligence Supervised Learning Assignment

Introduction

Goal of the Project : To study what factor and how they would impact the landing distance of a commercial flight which will eventually reduce the risk of landing overrun.

Data Used: Landing data (landing distance and other parameters) from 800 commercial flights (not real data set but simulated from statistical models).

Data

Variable Dictionary:
1. Aircraft: The make of an aircraft (Boeing or Airbus).
2. Duration (in minutes): Flight duration between taking off and landing. The duration of a normal flight should always be greater than 40min.
3. No_pasg: The number of passengers in a flight.
4. Speed_ground (in miles per hour): The ground speed of an aircraft when passing over the threshold of the runway. If its value is less than 30MPH or greater than 140MPH, then the landing would be considered as abnormal.
5. Speed_air (in miles per hour): The air speed of an aircraft when passing over the threshold of the runway. If its value is less than 30MPH or greater than 140MPH, then the landing would be considered as abnormal.
6. Height (in meters): The height of an aircraft when it is passing over the threshold of the runway. The landing aircraft is required to be at least 6 meters high at the threshold of the runway.
7. Pitch (in degrees): Pitch angle of an aircraft when it is passing over the threshold of the runway.
8. Distance (in feet): The landing distance of an aircraft. More specifically, it refers to the distance between the threshold of the runway and the point where the aircraft can be fully stopped. The length of the airport runway is typically less than 6000 feet.

Variable ‘Risky Landing’

Create the new binary variable ‘Risky Landing’

The aim of our study is to develop a logistic regression model to predict if the aircraft would overshoot the runway or not. To develop a logistic model, we will create a new binary variable ‘risk landing’, using the ‘Distance’ column. It’s value would be 0 or 1 based on whether the landing distance is normal or abnormal. We also changed the data type of aircraft from character to factor.

faa_new$aircraft <- as.factor(faa_new$aircraft)

faa_new$risky_landing <- ifelse(faa_new$distance > 3000,1,0)

Analysis:Risky Landing

Risky Landing Analysis
Single Factor Regression Analysis for Risky Landing 

FAA_final = mutate(faa_train, aircraft_num = ifelse(aircraft == "airbus", 1, 0))
varnames <- names(FAA_final)
df <- FAA_final[, which(!names(FAA_final) %in% c("aircraft_num"))]
varnames <- names(df)
signif_table <- data.frame(variable_name = character(), regression_coefficient = numeric(), odds_ratio = numeric(), pvalue = numeric(), coefficient_direction = character(), stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
i = 1 
for (var in varnames[!varnames %in% c("risky_landing")]) { 
  Y <- df$risky_landing 
  X <- unlist(df[, var]) 
  reg <- glm(Y ~ X, family = binomial) 
  signif_table[i, 1] = var 
  signif_table[i, 2] = abs(summary(reg)$coefficients[2, 1]) 
  signif_table[i, 3] = exp(summary(reg)$coefficients[2, 1])
  signif_table[i, 4] = summary(reg)$coefficients[2, 4] 
  signif_table[i, 5] = ifelse(summary(reg)$coefficients[2, 1] > 0, "Positive", "Negative") 
  i = i + 1 
}
signif_table <- signif_table %>% arrange(pvalue)

Next we standardize the variables and then perform single factor regression analysis and we get the same results. 

df <- FAA_final[, which(!names(FAA_final) %in% c("aircraft_num"))]
varnames <- names(df)
StdCoeff_table <- data.frame(variable_name = character(), regression_coefficient = numeric(), odds_ratio = numeric(), pvalue = numeric(), coefficient_direction = character(), stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
i = 1 
for (var in varnames[!varnames %in% c("risky_landing")]) { 
  Y <- df$risky_landing 
  X <- if (var == "aircraft") {
    unlist(df[, var]) 
    } else { 
    unlist(scale(df[, var])) 
    }
  reg <- glm(Y ~ X, family = binomial)
  signif_table[i, 1] = var 
  signif_table[i, 2] = abs(summary(reg)$coefficients[2, 1]) 
  signif_table[i, 3] = exp(summary(reg)$coefficients[2, 1]) 
  signif_table[i, 4] = summary(reg)$coefficients[2, 4] 
  signif_table[i, 5] = ifelse(summary(reg)$coefficients[2, 1] > 0, "Positive", "Negative")
  i = i + 1 
}
signif_table <- signif_table %>% arrange(pvalue)

Full Model

Final Full Model for Risky Landing
Now we build a Final Full Model for Risky Landing.
We only choose speed_ground and aircraft as the predictor variables.
We remove duration, no_pasg and pitch as they are not significant based on the above analysis.
We also remove speed_air as it is highly correlated with speed_ground and has a lot of missing values.

final_model_risky_landing <- glm(risky_landing ~ speed_ground + aircraft, data = FAA_final, family = binomial) 

summary(final_model_risky_landing)

• The risky landing can be expressed as a linear function of the above two parameters.
• Keeping other factors constant, a unit increase in speed ground increases the odds of risky landing by 2.814.
• Keeping other factors constant, a unit increase in pitch increases the odds of risky landing by 21.673.

Classification Tree

What is Classification Tree?
Classification and regression trees are machine-learning methods for constructing prediction models from data.
The models are obtained by recursively partitioning the data space and fitting a simple prediction model within each partition.
As a result, the partitioning can be represented graphically as a decision tree.
Classification trees are designed for dependent variables that take a finite number of unordered values, with prediction error measured in terms of misclassification cost.
The dataset contains 800 observations and 8 variables.
400 observations from Airbus flights and 400 from Boeing flights.

Decision_Tree

Conclusion

The dataset we chose for out model presented quite a few challenges:
• The recommended distance for safety landing is under 6000 feet, and our response variable has predominantly 0’s (safe landing distance) for majority of the planes, versus 1’s (risky landing). This may have caused the model to inaccurately predict the risk landing factor. We had a few disagreements as to how to address the issue, i.e. which cutoff distance to choose as a selection criterium.
• Also, the data seems to underestimate the landing distance of the planes’ quite dramatically. For example, A380 requires at least 7800 feet for take-off/landing depending on the weather and some other conditions.
• The other issue was the multicollinearity between the independent variables (between speed ground and distance, speed air and speed ground). One of the possible solutions, besides excluding one of the speed variables, is to create interaction terms. One of them is number of passengers divided by the ground speed, the other one is the height of the plane divided by the number of passengers.

Compare

After comparing the above parameters, we can say the best model is Classification Tree for the prediction of landing distance being within the risky category or not.

The Federal Aviation Administration can find this analysis valuable for designing the airports.
There are some types of planes that need landing run way to be more than 6000 like cargo carrires etc, but for small local airports this prediction will assist the FAA architects to plan the airport.
The similar type of analysis can also be done for other heavy planes.
